","Abt 1480":"about 1480","1476":"1476","1560":"1560","1480":"1480","1506":"1506","Abt 1504":"about 1504","Aft 1506":"after 1506","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Shenton, Leicestershire, England":"Shenton, Leicestershire, England","Cheshire,, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wintley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Windley, a place in Derbyshire named from Old English <i>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alexander Wintley was born about 1480, in Leicestershire, England. He married Mrs. Alexander Wintley about 1504, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1506, in Shenton, Leicestershire, England, and was buried in Shenton, Leicestershire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1480–Aft 1506":"umbes 1480–pärast 1506","1476–Female":"1476–Surnud","1506–1560":"1506–1560","1480–1506":"1480–1506","Abt 1480":"umbes 1480","1476":"1476","1560":"1560","1480":"1480","1506":"1506","Abt 1504":"umbes 1504","Aft 1506":"pärast 1506","Leice